From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: nix-on-z <nix-on-z@s390x>
Date: Sun, 19 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix T64 transposeBytes byte extraction on big-endian

`transposeBytes<T>` extracts the k-th byte of a native integer via
memory aliasing:

    const UInt8 * value8 = reinterpret_cast<const UInt8 *>(&value);
    matrix8[64 * k + col] = value8[k];

On little-endian `value8[k]` is the k-th least-significant byte.
On big-endian `value8[k]` is the k-th MOST-significant byte, so the
bytes end up stored in the transpose matrix in reversed positional
order.

`reverseTransposeBytes<T>` however uses arithmetic shifts:

    value |= static_cast<U>(matrix8[64 * k + col]) << (8 * k);

which unambiguously places matrix row k into value's k-th
least-significant byte. That is correct on both LE and BE.

The asymmetry means a T64 round-trip on BE silently reverses the byte
positions within each value. Combined with patch 0101's
`unalignedLoadLittleEndian` load/store (which byte-swaps the column
buffer so the transpose operates on a logical LE value), the result
is that a UInt16 input of 256 (0x0100) decodes to 1 (0x0001) and 512
(0x0200) decodes to 2 (0x0002) — a whole-byte swap within each value.

Empirically reproducible on s390x with stock patches applied:

    CREATE TABLE t1 (x UInt16 CODEC(T64, ZSTD))
      ENGINE=MergeTree ORDER BY tuple();
    INSERT INTO t1 VALUES (0),(256),(512);
    SELECT x FROM t1;
    -- produces: 0, 1, 2   (expected: 0, 256, 512)

Fix: make `transposeBytes` byte extraction shift-based so it is
value-preserving (endian-agnostic) and symmetric with
`reverseTransposeBytes`. On LE the compiler lowers
`(value >> (8*k)) & 0xFF` to the same byte-load as the memory
aliasing did before, so codegen is unchanged on the common path.

This is the counterpart of the load/store byte-swap in patch 0101:
with that patch the values inside `buf[]` live in a logical LE
domain, and the transpose must respect that domain rather than the
native byte order of the host.

Tests affected: 00870_t64_codec, 00871_t64_codec_signed, and every
other T64-using test that was previously decoding to zeros or
byte-swapped values on s390x.
---
--- a/src/Compression/CompressionCodecT64.cpp
+++ b/src/Compression/CompressionCodecT64.cpp
@@ -287,27 +287,28 @@ void transpose64x8(UInt64 * src_dst)
 template <typename T>
 void transposeBytes(T value, UInt64 * matrix, UInt32 col)
 {
     UInt8 * matrix8 = reinterpret_cast<UInt8 *>(matrix);
-    const UInt8 * value8 = reinterpret_cast<const UInt8 *>(&value);
+    using U = std::make_unsigned_t<T>;
+    const U uvalue = static_cast<U>(value);
 
     if constexpr (sizeof(T) > 4)
     {
-        matrix8[64 * 7 + col] = value8[7];
-        matrix8[64 * 6 + col] = value8[6];
-        matrix8[64 * 5 + col] = value8[5];
-        matrix8[64 * 4 + col] = value8[4];
+        matrix8[64 * 7 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 7));
+        matrix8[64 * 6 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 6));
+        matrix8[64 * 5 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 5));
+        matrix8[64 * 4 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 4));
     }
 
     if constexpr (sizeof(T) > 2)
     {
-        matrix8[64 * 3 + col] = value8[3];
-        matrix8[64 * 2 + col] = value8[2];
+        matrix8[64 * 3 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 3));
+        matrix8[64 * 2 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 2));
     }
 
     if constexpr (sizeof(T) > 1)
-        matrix8[64 * 1 + col] = value8[1];
+        matrix8[64 * 1 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue >> (8 * 1));
 
-    matrix8[64 * 0 + col] = value8[0];
+    matrix8[64 * 0 + col] = static_cast<UInt8>(uvalue);
 }
 
 template <typename T>
